From: nvukobratTT <nvukobratTT@users.noreply.github.com>
Date: Thu, 9 Apr 2026 00:19:14 +0000
Subject: [PATCH 5/8] feat(TTNN): add TTNNCheckDRAMBudget compile-time DRAM OOM
 detection pass

Adds a new MLIR pass ttnn-check-dram-budget that runs after ttnn-deallocate
and detects DRAM OOM conditions at compile time instead of letting the program
hang silently at runtime (see GH #11).

The pass simulates tensor lifetimes using a first-fit freelist allocator --
mirroring what tt-metal does at runtime.  This catches two failure modes:

1. Classic total-budget OOM (estimated peak > per-chip budget)
2. Fragmentation-induced OOM: total free DRAM is sufficient but no single
   contiguous block is large enough for the requested tensor.  This is the
   actual failure mode for Mochi 10B at seq_len=2080 on 4-chip SPMD TP:
   the sum estimator shows ~12-14 GiB peak vs 34 GiB budget (PASS) but the
   first-fit freelist correctly signals allocation failure.

Implementation:
- FreeListAllocator: minimal first-fit allocator over a sorted vector of
  FreeRange structs.  Freed ranges are merged with neighbours.  All sizes
  are rounded up to DRAM_ALIGNMENT (32 bytes) to match tt-metal.
- tensorBase DenseMap tracks where each live tensor was placed so the
  exact range can be returned at DeallocateOp time.
- For symmetric SPMD TP the IR already reflects per-chip tensor sizes after
  the SPMD sharding pass -- one freelist with the per-chip budget suffices.
- Warning emitted at 90% utilisation as an early signal.
- Two distinct error messages: fragmentation OOM names the requested block
  size, the largest available block, and the total free bytes.

GH: https://github.com/nvukobratTT/tt-xla/issues/11 (Solution 3 v2)
